description.narrative:
This project will continue and expand UNIDO work rendered in support of the local production of essential generic medicines in developing and least developed countries (DCs/LDCs) that began with funding from Germany in January 2006. With phase 3 of the pertinent global project foreseen for conclusion at end-2012, the present proposal has been prepared against the background of a dual pledge from Germany of renewed funding, i.e. (i) by leaving her unutilized balances with UNIDO for consolidating and enhancing the organization’s work in the area of local pharmaceutical production (LPP), and (ii) by offering the financing of a fourth phase of the global project for 2013. The present proposal acknowledges the compatibility of both funding commitments and thus – as a means to maximize synergies for implementation – offers a combined response for a project period of 28 months.

Substantively, the project will build on the progress and results of the past, notably the milestone achievement in phase 3, following UNIDO’s entering into a partnership with the African Union Commission (AUC) in July 2011. The partnership culminated in the joint preparation and formal adoption at highest AU political levels (AU Conference of Ministers of Health, AU Heads of State Summit) of a “Business Plan” (BP) for the accelerated implementation of the 2007 AU Pharmaceutical Manufacturing Plan for Africa (PMPA) in mid-2012. Owned by the AU, the PMPA BP is designed to become the main reference document for action in support of LPP in the years ahead. UNIDO’s offer to support the BP’s envisaged implementation as a core partner has been welcomed by the AUC. Therefore, in addition to the continuation, deepening and further spread-out of established UNIDO interventions, the present proposal seeks to render specific contributions for the start-up phase of the BP’s implementation.
Advisory and capacity-building interventions will be geared to improving the operating environment of pharmaceutical manufacturers and thus address key constraints at policy and institutional levels. Specifically, the main planned activity clusters comprise the following:
o Support the implementation of select dimensions of the pharmaceutical manufacturing sector strategies that were developed and agreed by national stakeholders in earlier project phases (Ghana, Kenya);
o Jointly with WHO, support Viet Nam in translating the results of the recently concluded pharma industry and LPP policy assessment into concrete follow-up towards the industry’s uplifting;
o Commence and escort sector strategy development processes for the pharmaceutical industry in two additional countries (to be selected from among Mozambique, Nigeria, Uganda, UR Tanzania, Zimbabwe).
o Further strengthen the advocacy and servicing capabilities of the Southern African Generics Medicines Association (SAGMA) and similar bodies in other sub-regions; support the newly founded pan-African apex body (Federation of African Pharmaceutical Manufacturer Associations/ FAPMA) during start-up;
o Continue and expand the support to St Luke Foundation (UR Tanzania) in delivering modular training courses on industrial pharmacy;
o Conceptualize, elaborate, refine, test and/or apply a number of tools (solution packages) designed to support further pharma sector development interventions, both within PMPA BP implementation and without (GMP Roadmap, EML risk assessment, HR Development, access to technology, development of new drug formulations, business linkages and partnership platform);
o Support the early PMPA BP implementation in three ways: (i) Set-up the institutional/ management structure (including consortium of core partners, e.g. AU, UNIDO, ADB, NEPAD, WHO, others); (ii) Engage in fundraising to ensure broader and longer-term implementation assistance; and (iii) Provide start-up implementation support to select AU Member States.
The (informal) collaboration started earlier on with WHO will be intensified, while a UN to UN Agency Contribution Agreement will be concluded with UNCTAD for the provision of specialized services in the field of intellectual property (TRIPS and Public Health/ TRIPS Flexibilities) to complement project interventions.
Africa will remain the main regional focus for the project given that this is where the access to drugs crisis is most profound, where there is substantial political interest in the area, and where the previous projects have gained the most experience. This will be complemented, however, by activities in Asia, responding to government requests (Viet Nam, and possibly Myanmar).
